{
  "texts": [
    "Specifically, discourse analysis of shifting platform policies and narratives around misinformation can surface logics shaping content interventions [110].",
    "Ethnographic observations within platform governance teams examining changes in day-to-day content moderation practices and norms explicate on-the-ground contexts underlying computational trends [105].Triangulating large-scale quantitative indicators tracking activities like volumes of content removed via notice-andtakedown procedures with qualitative interviews tracing platforms' procedural shifts and implementation challenges might allows cross-validating findings across methods [74].Similarly, in-depth comparative case study analyses of platform responses across risky societal events before vs. after DSA adoption can be reinforced by interrupted time series statistical models estimating misinformation diffusion trends [19].Careful coordination in framing inquiries, timing data collection, and integrating computational and qualitative approaches enables producing robust, multidimensional insights.",
    "As reported by [178], following established guidelines for mixed methods research design is key to effectively triangulate findings across approaches when evaluating complex policy interventions like the DSA.To summarize the current section, Fig. 1 maps between research approaches, goals, and stakeholders for a comprehensive understanding of the research landscape in DSA studies.",
    "The figure was obtained through a methodological framework exposed in Appendix 3.1.",
    "Methodological challenges and limitationsThe proposed research agenda aims to enable multifaceted assessment of the DSA's impacts across stakeholders."
  ]
}